I think your aggro section is a tad off. Coming from someone who plays both tanks (Monk and Paladin) and casters (Wizard) I have seen aggro work differently. So some of this information is gleemed from my experiences as riding the aggro line as a Wizard with spells, riding the aggro line with my Monk (as well as pulling - you'd be surprised) and trying to keep aggro with my Paladin.<br>
<br>
Most important thing to remember is that aggro varies depending on mob and what zone that mob is in. So a goblin in RunnyEye may or may not act the same as a goblin in High Keep.<br>
<br>
Now as many know, aggro is affected by distance between you and target (left out of the FAQ btw).  Once you have attacked a target, you have entered its hate list but how close you are determines how many aggro points you have built up.<br>
<br>
Also, meleeing adds more aggro points whether you are landing those hits or not. How fast you are (even if your still missing) determines how much the mob hates you. The faster you are, the higher you will be on the hate list. If a Wizard draws aggro to themselves they should <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> not</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->:<br>
1) Run around in circles<br>
2) Melee, and/or<br>
3) Cast damage spells<br>
<br>
Only time rule #3 should be broken is if said Wizard is stunning the mob to move away, and/or thinks the mob is close enough to being dead they can take the abuse. Other than that, the party healer may get annoyed with having yet another person to heal.<br>
<br>
Remember that casting spells near a mob add aggro. Not all spells add the same amount of aggro points but the Skin series seems to add the most with Damage spells closely behind.<br>
<br>
Level is also key. The lower you are the more delicious you look. Not only that but once the gap between you and the monster comes closer, your aggro range reduces. When the monster becomes a dark blue con and light blue, the aggro range becomes even smaller.<br>
<br>
Tricks on Aggro for AoE<br>
Many times you can launch an AoE spell without drawing aggro to yourself. Just like you hold yourself back with DD spells factor the damage from your AoE in the same manner. Target the main tank and cast your AoE. If you are at a good distance away (i.e. Pillars are great for this technique) and you did not out aggro the tank on the mob he is taunting/tanking than you should be safe and all monsters will attack the tank. When that monster dies however, some of the mobs affected in that AE blast <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> may</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> come to attack you.<br>
<br>
What can save that from happening is aggro lists are passed by mobs so by the time the 1st is killed the main tank may have built up enough aggro on the others. Before you AoE again, just remember the damage you inflicted earlier.<br>
<br>
This technique should only be used if the group knows in advance. Do not piss off the Enchanters. If they are not expecting this and every one else in the party is expecting the same old mez rest, fight one at a time routine you could really screw things up.<br>
<br>
<br>
